They are very personable and even if you have a waiter, there are others who will attend you. I've had other waiters come by to pick up plates, fill our drinks, and even ask how we're doing. The food is worth every penny. I had just come back from a trip to Florida where a sushi restaurant was awarded for the best sushi, and despite it being good sushi, it still does not compare to Tsunami. Tsunami is on a different scale of greatness. For starters we had the squid salad. They have the best squid salad. They do not skimp out on the squid either, unlike other restaurants. These are the rolls we tried. The one on the left with the orange rue is Father Calai. The one below it is the Dynamite Roll (I ate one before I took the picture). The next plate is the Bon Temp Roll (with crawfish), Hung Lo (center), and Don Tuan (topped with avocado slices). We used eel sauce and mayonnaise as alternative dipping sauces (in addition to soy sauce). Even their ginger slices are delicious and were readily consumed. We finished our meal with mochi ice cream. How we had room is beyond me. My friend and I were pleasantly stuffed. I wish I could bring this restaurant with me to Texas. I would recommend it to everyone. Thank you again, Eric, for accommodating us so well. And you too, Chris. You are the fastest sushi roller. And thank you to our waiter, David, for making sure we were well taken care of.

Lafayettes premiere Sushi restaurant. There is no shortage of options when it comes to sushi in Lafayette, and that makes the fact that Tsunami has managed to stay at the head of the pack all the more impressive. Whether you are eating in the main dining hall, or in the more casual Lounge ( a large adjoined dining area and bar), a weekend night in Tsunami is abuzz with an energy that, for better or worse, perfectly encapsulates the spirit of Lafayette. Value is generally the most common criticism levied against Tsunami, and while it's true that you probably will not have the tastiest or cheapest roll in Lafayette, Tsunami is guaranteed to give you and your friends a night you will be talking about for weeks.

My friends and I went for happy hour when lemon drop martinis were $5 and were upcharged $7 for a flavor (I ordered a blueberry lemon drop martini and a raspberry lemon drop martini)!! We weren’t told about the upcharge until we got the bill. I’ve gone plenty of times during happy hour and was never charged for a flavored drink. The waitress could have a least informed us about the price difference, but she didn’t. To me that is just unacceptable. When we asked for a manager, nothing was really done about the problem. When we ordered raspberry lemon drop martinis at the table they were yellow, went to the bar and ordered the same drink (raspberry lemon drop) and they were red. So obviously they added no extra flavoring to the ones we ordered during dinning, but we were still changed an extra $7 which is just inexcusable. Save yourself some money and just go somewhere else. If I could give them no stars I would.
